    <h2>Network Topologies</h2>
    <!--Why do we need this i've never even seen it come up once ever-->
    <p>
        - A network topology is the physical structure of the network (like, the placement of cables and stuff).<br>
        - Different network models (P2P/Client-Server) can be used on a topology.<br>
        - Many network topologies are in use, but the ones you need to care about are star and mesh.
    </p>
    <h3>Star Topology</h3>
    <p>
        - A star topology has a central main switch (or switches), which all other devices on the network connect
        to.<br>
        - You can think of it as if the central switch is the star, and each device is on the end of each
        of the star's points.
    </p>
    <h3>Mesh Topology</h3>
    <p>
        - A mesh topology is where all (well, most usually) computers are connected to all other computers.<br>
        - Where <i>every</i> computer is connected to <i>every other</i> computer, this is 'full' mesh topology.<br>
        - Mesh networks are most common with IoT (Internet of Things), for example Amazon's Ring doorbells can all
        communicate with each other so if your internet goes down, your Ring doorbell might be able to pickup
        an internet signal from your neighbour's one.<br>
        - You may have seen 'mesh networks' advertised as a way to get full WiFi coverage, they're called this
        because each (puck?) you place around the building has the ability to communicate with all the others to
        intelligently connect you to the one with the best signal.<br>
        - A partial mesh topology is when not <i>every</i> device is connected together, which requires less cables
        and less hardware in general, but there are still redundant paths for data to take.
    </p>
    <h3>Comparison Table</h3>
    <table>
        <tr>
            <th>Aspect</th>
            <th>Star Topology</th>
            <th>Mesh Topology</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><b>Definition</b></td>
            <td>A network topology where each device is connected to a central hub or switch.</td>
            <td>A network topology where each device is connected to every other device in the network, either directly
                (fully connected) or partially.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><b>Cost</b></td>
            <td>Generally lower cost because it requires fewer cables and connections than a full mesh network.</td>
            <td>Typically higher cost due to the large number of cables and connections required, especially in a fully
                connected mesh.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><b>Scalability</b></td>
            <td>Highly scalable. New devices can be added easily without affecting the rest of the network.</td>
            <td>Less scalable, particularly in a fully connected mesh, as adding new devices increases the complexity
                and number of connections exponentially.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><b>Reliability</b></td>
            <td>Less reliable if the central hub fails, as the entire network can go down. However, individual device
                failures usually do not affect the network.</td>
            <td>Highly reliable because multiple paths exist between any two devices. The failure of one device or
                connection does not typically disrupt the entire network.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><b>Complexity</b></td>
            <td>Low complexity. The network is simple to design, implement, and manage.</td>
            <td>High complexity. Managing and configuring the network is more challenging due to the multiple
                connections.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><b>Performance</b></td>
            <td>Performance is generally good because data passes through only one or two devices (hub and the
                destination device), minimizing latency.</td>
            <td>Potential for excellent performance due to multiple paths, but can suffer from increased latency in
                large, fully connected networks due to the number of hops.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><b>Maintenance</b></td>
            <td>Easy to maintain as troubleshooting is straightforward. Issues are often localized to a single device or
                the central hub.</td>
            <td>Challenging to maintain due to the large number of connections. Identifying and fixing issues can be
                more difficult.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><b>Security</b></td>
            <td>Centralized security measures can be implemented effectively, but if the central hub is compromised, the
                whole network is at risk.</td>
            <td>More secure as it is harder to compromise the entire network. Attacking one device does not necessarily
                affect others.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><b>Data Collisions</b></td>
            <td>Few data collisions as each device communicates with the central hub, reducing the likelihood of
                collisions.</td>
            <td>Low likelihood of data collisions because of multiple paths available, though it depends on the specific
                implementation.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><b>Implementation</b></td>
            <td>Easy to implement and expand. Ideal for small to medium-sized networks.</td>
            <td>Complex to implement, particularly in fully connected networks. More suitable for large networks
                requiring high reliability.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><b>Network Failure Impact</b></td>
            <td>If the central hub fails, the entire network goes down. However, individual device failures have limited
                impact.</td>
            <td>Network failure impact is minimal, as there are multiple paths for data to travel. A single device
                failure usually has little to no impact.</td>
        </tr>
    </table>
